ce:section.ce:para:
As shown in Fig. 3
                        A, the fluorescence intensity strengthened with the increase in ATP concentration. The linear concentration range (Fig. 3B) between fluorescence intensity and ATP concentration was from 0.3 to 2.0 mM, as represented by the equation y = 176.67 x + 335.51 (R2 = 0.9916). The limit of detection (LOD) was 0.27 mM (3δ, n = 11). This result indicated that ABA could effectively recognized ATP and that the fabricated bioassay was an efficient bio-system for the detection of ATP both qualitatively and quantitatively. Moreover, compared with other methods of ATP detection (Table 1
                        ), the response range of our method was closer to the actual intracellular ATP level, which was more conducive to intracellular ATP sensing. The selectivity of the AuNCs-GQDs system was based on the specific recognition of ABA toward ATP. We evaluated the specificity of the bio-system utilizing ATP analogues, including UTP, GTP, and CTP under the same experimental conditions and at the same concentration of 1.8 mM. Obviously, only ATP exhibited significant fluorescence enhancement, while UTP, CTP, and GTP exhibited no obvious fluorescence intensity enhancement compared with the blank control (Fig. 4
                        ), which demonstrated the high specificity of the designed biosensor.
